Mutational signatures analysis: refitting with known signatures

During this practical session, we will focus on the detection and interpretation of mutational signatures in real samples. Particularly, you’ll with perform the refitting mutational signature analysis.

The process of signature refitting involves measuring the impact of a specific set of signatures on the mutational profile of a sample. This is particularly valuable when analyzing mutational signatures in small groups or individual samples, as well as for comparing one’s own findings with established signatures and published research.

The data used in this section is publicly available WES data generated from Ji et at. 2020. The somatic variant calling was performed using Strelka2.

For that, we will work with this R package: MutationalPatterns.

Functions to load vcf.gz Strelka2 files

This function can open the Strelka2 somatic calls ( vcf.gz with SNVs) and extract the VAF, DP, number of alternative alleles…

# Function to load snp.vcf.gz from Strelka2
Load_vcf <- function(vcf_file){
  VCF <- as.data.frame(fread(cmd = paste("zgrep -v '##' ", vcf_file, sep = ''), sep = '\t'))
  VCF <- dplyr::rename(VCF, CHROM = `#CHROM`)
  VCF <- VCF[VCF$CHROM %in% c(paste('chr',seq(1,22), sep = ''),'chrX','chrY'),]
  
  # Parse the vcf to extract alternative counts
  # We keep only the PASS mutations
  VCF2 <- VCF[VCF$FILTER == 'PASS',]
  
  # Extract normal alternative counts
  VCF2 <- tidyr::separate(data = VCF2, col = NORMAL, sep = ':', 
                          into = c('N_DP','N_FDP','N_SDP','N_SUBDP','N_AU','N_CU','N_GU','N_TU'))
  VCF2$N_REF_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('N_',x['REF'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$N_ALT_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('N_',x['ALT'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$N_DP <- as.numeric(VCF2$N_DP) # We want this value to be considered as a number
  
  # Extract tumour alternative counts
  VCF2 <- tidyr::separate(data = VCF2, col = TUMOR, sep = ':', 
                          into = c('T_DP','T_FDP','T_SDP','T_SUBDP','T_AU','T_CU','T_GU','T_TU'))
  VCF2$T_REF_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('T_',x['REF'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$T_ALT_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('T_',x['ALT'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$T_DP <- as.numeric(VCF2$T_DP) # We want this value to be considered as a number
  
  # Too many columns for now, let's keep only the important ones
  VCF3 <- VCF2[,c('CHROM','POS','REF','ALT','QUAL','FILTER','N_DP','N_REF_COUNT','N_ALT_COUNT','T_DP','T_REF_COUNT','T_ALT_COUNT')]
  
  # Compute Variant Allele Frequency (VAF) in the matched normal sample
  VCF3$N_VAF <- VCF3$N_ALT_COUNT/VCF3$N_DP
  # Compute Variant Allele Frequency (VAF) in the tumour sample
  VCF3$T_VAF <- VCF3$T_ALT_COUNT/VCF3$T_DP
  return(VCF3)
}

Loading all data

We will work with 9 cSCC cancer samples (Ji et at. 2020). We already generated the somatic calls using Strelka2.

Let’s first of all check the number of files that we will load. Let’s first of all check the number of files that we will load. Please edit the path of DATA_FOLDER to the path of your data

# Directory with the Strelka calls
# Please edit this path to the desired one in your computer
DATA_FOLDER <- '~/Documents/EMBL/Projects/CancerGenomicsCourse/mutational_analysis_vcfs/'

files <- list.files(path=DATA_FOLDER, pattern = '*snvs.vcf.gz$', recursive = T)
files <- paste(DATA_FOLDER,files, sep = '/')
files <- files[!grepl('COLO', x = files)]

length(files)
## [1] 9


In order to save the calls of all these files in a single data frame automatically, we will use the next for loop:

count <- 1
Mut_calls <- NULL
for (file in files){
  # Load vcf.gz file
  # Function previously defined
  a <- Load_vcf(file)
  
  # Get sample ID
  # We extract the sample name from the full path
  sampleID <- rev(unlist(strsplit(x = file, split = '/')))[3]
  
  if (nrow(a) > 0){
    a <- cbind(sampleID,a)

    Mut_calls[[count]] <- a
    
    count <- count + 1
  }
}

# Usually faster than rbind in each iteration of the for loop
Mut_calls <- do.call("rbind", Mut_calls)

Filtering mutations

# Let's focus on the autosomal chromosomes
Mut_calls <- Mut_calls[Mut_calls$CHROM %in% paste('chr',seq(1,22), sep = ''),]
# At least a depth of coverage of 10x
Mut_calls <- Mut_calls[Mut_calls$T_DP >= 10,]

Mutation characteristics

In this example today, we will focus on SNVs. This package ( MutationalPatterns), works with GRanges objects. For these reasons, we will transform our data frame with mutations into a GRanges object:
It can be done with this function:

# Transform data.frame to genomic ranges object
# Create list of granges
GRmaker <- function(CALLS,GROUP){
  TEMP <- CALLS[CALLS$GROUP == GROUP,]
  GR <- with(TEMP, GRanges(CHROM, ranges=IRanges(POS, POS), REF = REF,ALT = ALT, VAF = T_VAF))
  seqlevelsStyle(GR) <- "UCSC"
  GenomeInfoDb::genome(GR) <- 'hg38'
  return (GR)
}


Once defined this function, we can execute it using our mutations data frame:

# This column will specify how to group the mutations
# For now, we use the sampleID, but it can be modified
Mut_calls$GROUP <- Mut_calls$sampleID

# Create list of granges
GROUPS <- unique(Mut_calls$GROUP)
G_lists <-  lapply(GROUPS, function(x) GRmaker(Mut_calls, x))
names(G_lists) <- GROUPS

Mutation spectrum

The mutation spectrum displays the proportionate contribution of each mutation type within the base substitution catalogs.
With the function mut_type_occurrences, you can count mutation type occurrences for all VCF objects in the GRangesList:

type_occurrences <- mut_type_occurrences(G_lists, ref_genome)

The function plot_spectrum is responsible for generating a plot that showcases the average relative contribution of the six base substitution types across all samples. Error bars indicate the 95% confidence interval across all samples.

p1 <- plot_spectrum(type_occurrences, indv_points = TRUE)
p1

96 mutation profile

The 96 mutation profile refers to a classification system that characterizes mutations based on the nucleotide context surrounding them. It considers all possible trinucleotide combinations (96 in total) and quantifies the frequency of specific mutation types within each context.

First we need to generate a 96 trinucleotide mutation count matrix using the function mut_matrix:

mut_mat <- mut_matrix(vcf_list = G_lists, ref_genome = ref_genome)
head(mut_mat)

# Plot with 96 profile context

Signature refitting

Find mathematically optimal contribution of COSMIC signatures (v3)

The process of signature refitting involves measuring the impact of a specific set of signatures on the mutational profile of a sample. This is particularly valuable when analyzing mutational signatures in small groups or individual samples, as well as for comparing one’s own findings with established signatures and published research.

In our case, we will work with the COSMIC SBS signatures (v3.2). we can load them directly from the package. In case you work with non-human species, you can download the mutational signatures from other species (or other human reference genome versions) here

# Getting known signatures
# COSMIC (v3.2) (Alexandrov et al. 2020)
signatures = get_known_signatures()
head(signatures[,1:5])

## [3,] 0.0001770314 5.230151e-05 0.00175070 0.01559871 0.001849630
## [4,] 0.0012802272 9.780282e-05 0.01220488 0.02949755 0.006608678

To avoid problems with the overfitting, and because we know that all these samples are coming from skin cancers, we will only interrogate COSMIC mutational signatures already found in these types of cancers (Alexandrov et al. 2020).

# Filter to prior knowledge in skin cancers
skin_sbs_alexandrov <- c('SBS1','SBS2','SBS5','SBS7a','SBS7b','SBS7c','SBS7d','SBS13','SBS32','SBS40')
signatures <- signatures[,colnames(signatures) %in% skin_sbs_alexandrov]


The function fit_to_signatures_strict calculates the best possible linear combination of mutational signatures, adhering to non-negative least-squares constraints, in order to reconstruct the mutation matrix with the highest degree of accuracy.

# Run the function
# max_delta parameter: Decreasing this number will make the refitting less strict, while increasing it will make the refitting more strict.
strict_refit <- fit_to_signatures_strict(mut_mat, signatures, max_delta = 0.004)


Now, we can get and plot the COSMIC contribution results to our samples (Abosulte contributions)

# Getting the contribution of each signature
fit_res_strict <- strict_refit$fit_res

# Absolute contribution
Plot_contribution_abs <- plot_contribution(fit_res_strict$contribution,
                  coord_flip = TRUE,
                  mode = "absolute"
)
Plot_contribution_abs


Or relative contribution:

# Relative contribution
Plot_contribution_rel <- plot_contribution(fit_res_strict$contribution,
                                           coord_flip = TRUE,
                                           mode = "relative"
)
Plot_contribution_rel

Evaluating the performance of the reconstruction

One of the most used methods for quantifying the performance of mutational signature analysis is using the cosine similarity. This is a measure used to quantify the similarity between two signature vectors. The cosine similarity calculates the cosine of the angle between two signature vectors, which indicates the degree of similarity or alignment between them.

MutationaPatterns: “…We can also plot the cosine similarity between the original and reconstructed matrix for all the samples. When a reconstructed profile has a cosine similarity of more than 0.95 with the original, the reconstructed profile is considered very good…”

# Check the quality of the reconstruction
Plot_reconstruciton_cos_sim <- plot_original_vs_reconstructed(mut_mat, fit_res_strict$reconstructed, 
                               y_intercept = 0.95)
Plot_reconstruciton_cos_sim
